What It Shows:
Threads_connected ‚Äî Number of currently open (active) connections to the MySQL server.

‚úÖ Example Output:
+-------------------+-------+
| Variable_name     | Value |
+-------------------+-------+
| Threads_connected | 12    |
SHOW STATUS LIKE 'Threads_connected';
=================================================================================================================================================

What to Monitor Like a Pro DBA After Increasing max_connections
üîç Metric	                    How to Check	                           What to Observe
üîµ Threads_connected	        SHOW STATUS LIKE 'Threads_connected';	      Real-time connected clients
üîµ Max_used_connections	SHOW STATUS LIKE 'Max_used_connections';      Historical peak usage
üîµ Connection_errors_*	        SHOW STATUS LIKE 'Connection_errors%';	      Any failed or rejected connections
üîµ Aborted_connects	        SHOW STATUS LIKE 'Aborted_connects';	      Interrupted connections
üü¢ Performance_schema	        Query from performance_schema.threads	      Idle vs active threads
üü¢ OS RAM usage	        free -m, top, htop	                      Check MySQL RSS memory
üü¢ Swap usage	                vmstat, top, free	                      Should be 0 (no swap)
üü¢ CPU Load                   	top, uptime, htop	                      Keep load average < CPU cores
üü° Slow_query_log         	Enable & monitor	                      Too many slow queries = overuse
üü† waits and locks	        Use sys.innodb_lock_waits, performance_schema Identify locking due to overload

========================================================================================================================================================

‚úÖ After You Increase
Enable performance_schema if not already.

Monitor using:
SELECT * FROM performance_schema.threads;
Check if many threads are in Sleep state ‚Äî possible connection leaks.

====================================================================================================================================================

1. üîÑ Identify Slow or Blocked Threads
Query:

SELECT * 
       FROM performance_schema.threads  
       WHERE PROCESSLIST_TIME > 60 
       AND PROCESSLIST_COMMAND NOT IN ('Sleep', 'Daemon');

Helps find long-running queries.
Investigate PROCESSLIST_INFO field to see what SQL is stuck.

====================================================================================================================================================
Find Idle Sleepers (Connection Leaks)

SELECT * 
      FROM performance_schema.threads 
      WHERE PROCESSLIST_COMMAND = 'Sleep' 
      AND PROCESSLIST_TIME > 300;

Look for apps holding idle connections unnecessarily.
Use this to adjust wait_timeout or apply connection pooling.

======================================================================================================================================================================================
 Monitor High Memory Usage Per Thread

SELECT THREAD_ID, NAME, PROCESSLIST_USER, TOTAL_MEMORY, MAX_TOTAL_MEMORY 
FROM performance_schema.threads 
ORDER BY TOTAL_MEMORY DESC 
LIMIT 5;
Look for memory-heavy threads ‚Äî may indicate:

Bad queries
Memory leak in thread buffers
Abusive users
======================================================================================================================================================================================
 Track Query Content

SELECT THREAD_ID, PROCESSLIST_USER, PROCESSLIST_INFO 
FROM performance_schema.threads 
WHERE PROCESSLIST_INFO IS NOT NULL 
ORDER BY PROCESSLIST_TIME DESC 
LIMIT 5;
Identify the actual SQL being run.

Useful for EXPLAIN plan analysis.
======================================================================================================================================================================================
üö¶ Thread Type Breakdown (Health Check)

SELECT TYPE, COUNT(*) AS count 
FROM performance_schema.threads 
GROUP BY TYPE;
Helps identify if too many foreground (user) threads are active at once ‚Äî may need pooling or traffic limiting.


======================================================================================================================================================================================
Find Last Server Restart Time----------------------------------------------------------------------------[MAX_USED_CONNECTIONS]
To understand how recent the value is:


SHOW GLOBAL STATUS LIKE 'Uptime';

This tells you how many seconds MySQL has been running. You can convert that into a date/time:

